<TEXT>
many americans should avoid taxdeferred 
savings plans such as iras because they merely shift income to a 
time when theyll be subject to higher tax rates a private research 
group says 
many middleincome retirees are discovering their marginal tax 
rate is up to four times higher than the rate they paid while 
working the national center for policy analysis a nonprofit 
group based in dallas said in a report released tuesday 
for many people the promise of taxdeferred savings is a cruel 
hoax the study said 
many retirees are worse off because they put their savings in 
iras rather than ordinary savings accounts the study said adding 
that many younger people also would be better off avoiding 
taxdeferred savings programs which include iras and 401ks 
the higher tax rates for the elderly exist because some social 
security benefits now are taxed and some elderly people pay a new 
surtax for medicare coverage against catastrophic illnesses the 
report said 
these two taxes combined can raise the marginal tax rates of 
elderly retirees as much as 37 percentage points said aldona 
robbins a former treasury department economist and a coauthor of 
the study 
for example an elderly widow with 24000 of income from 
interest dividends and a pension in addition to her social security 
benefits faces a 1989 marginal tax rate of 483 percent on income 
from savings the study said without the social security and 
medicare taxes she would be in the 15 percent federal income tax 
bracket 
the value of iras company pensions and other taxdeferred 
savings has been severely eroded for about 60 percent of todays 
workers by the two taxes the group said 
the report warned that the higher tax rates for the elderly 
jeopardize the nations ability to stimulate the personal savings 
needed to fuel investment in the us economy and increase 
productivity 
under the current system about 70 billion per year is 
deposited into taxdeferred savings by younger people not yet aware 
that they are deferring taxes to the time when they will be facing 
the highest marginal tax rates the study said once this fact 
is widely known the effect on saving in the us will be 
devastating 
the study recommended abolishing both the social security and 
medicare taxes or at least changing the tax treatment of retirement 
savings perhaps by allowing people to pay taxes on deposits to 
savings programs at the point when their marginal tax rates are 
lower 
under the 1983 social security revisions half of all social 
security benefits are subject to federal income tax if half the 
benefits plus all nonsocial security income exceed 25000 for an 
individual or 32000 for a couple for these people 50 cents of 
the social security benefit is taxed for each dollar of additional 
income 
the medicare surcharge for the elderly was approved by congress 
last year to help finance coverage of catastrophic illnesses in 
1989 a 15 percent surtax is imposed on federal income tax 
liabilities over 150 affecting about 40 of percent of those 65 and 
older with the surtax rising to 28 percent by 1993 the maximum 
surtax payment is capped at 800 per person in 1989 and rises to 
1050 in 1993 
</TEXT>
