3091 million pounds of product weight in 1988 from 845 million 
pounds in 1980 
based on shipments through june this years frozen potato 
exports are up 27 percent from last year with french fries 
accounting for 88 percent of the volume 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
an agriculture department scientist is trying 
to make plant seeds take a nap and then wake up refreshed and ready 
to germinate 
research chemist sharon sowa of the departments agricultural 
research service is seeking ways of preserving seeds from a wide 
variety of plants including wheat passion fruit and guayule a 
natural substitute for rubber 
the sleep technique also could be used to prepare seeds for 
surgery by scientists who want to develop new plant varieties 
that can resist diseases withstand drought or add additional 
nutrients to diets 
in a report by the agency sowa said her goal was to treat 
seeds some day much like doctors treat their patients in surgery 
the same anesthetics such as nitrous oxide laughing gas that are 
used to slow human respiration during surgery also slow the life 
processes inside seeds 
sowa works at the usdas national seed laboratory fort collins 
colo where vast collections of plant species are held in cold 
storage the facility is maintained as insurance against seeds 
becoming extinct and as a resource for plant breeders 
nitrous oxide is what we call a permeable molecule it goes in 
and out of plant cells very easily without causing any damage 
she said exactly how it works to slow respiration in humans and 
seeds is unknown 
sowa said that on tests of snap beans a mixture of 80 percent 
nitrous oxide and air was blown over the seeds slowing cell 
respiration in the beans by 35 percent enough to anesthetize the 
seeds 
half an hour later she revived the seeds by exposing them to 
fresh air sowa said all the seeds eventually woke up and germinated 
normally 
</TEXT>
