<TEXT>
schools colleges and universities stand to 
lose federal aid unless they prove they have tough antidrug use 
policies with stiff penalties for use sale or distribution of 
illicit drugs 
the antidrug strategy unveiled by president bush on tuesday 
night also would pay for altenative schools for youths with drug 
habits and encourage states to declare schools as drugfree zones 
colleges and universities already have conditions for receiving 
federal aid new laws require them to ensure that illegal drugs are 
not being used by employees on the job and to have studentaid 
recipients certify that they do not use drugs 
the new strategy drafted by william bennett director of the 
national drug control policy office would require colleges to 
develop specific punishments for students who use illegal drugs the 
plans will be required as a condition for any federal aid including 
grants and contracts as well as student aid 
this is the primary goal of prevention to see to it that 
americans especially school children never start down a slippery 
slope of drug use that begins with experimentation but can 
culminate in dependency according to the drug strategy document 
for those school children and adults who have already begun to use 
drugs the goal is a rather different one to get them to stop 
elementary and secondary schools would lose federal aid if they 
failed to implement specific punishments for students caught 
possessing using or selling drugs 
american schools have been educating students about drugs for 
more than 20 years statistics show that about 99 percent of high 
schools and 87 percent of elementary schools offer antidrug 
lessons and even some kindergartens offer them 
but the national drug strategy stressed that schoolbased 
prevention programs should be reinforced by tough but fair school 
policies on use possession and distribution of drugs 
voicing his support for bushs clear tough blueprint for a 
drugfree nation education secretary lauro cavazos urged 
educators and parents to resolve to eliminate once and for all 
this threat to american education 
keith geiger new president of the national education 
association agreed that bush laid out a challenge for all of us 
and stressed that were ready to work 
in general the proposal was certainly well intentioned and 
means to do the right thing but is not adequate to meet the 
problem said lou nayman of the american federation of teachers 
it spoke to the goals the kinds of things that need to be 
accomplished but really did not supply any significant resources to 
match the objectives 
bennett singled out the simple and straightforward anne 
arundel county md drug policies that immediately expel any 
student caught selling or distributing drugs when a student is 
caught using or possessing drugs the school notifies the police 
calls his parents and suspends him for one to five days 
the education department has 3545 million budgeted for drug 
prevention programs in the current fiscal year with 83 percent 
going for state and local programs that compares with only 3 
million budgeted for drug education in 1986 
in the next fiscal year the administration is seeking 25 
million more for emergency drug education grants intended for urban 
areas with major drug problems 
the new strategy will encourage states to enact legislation that 
protects schools as drugfree zones about 14 states have failed to 
propose or pass such legislation said the document 
last year new jerseys drugfree school zones resulted in 
arrests of 8800 people statewide 
the plan is for all public and private schools to become 
drugfree zones where dealers and users caught on school grounds 
will face penalties of five years for possession and up to 40 years 
and fines of 40000 for distribution 
</TEXT>
