an estimated 4 million americans use illegal 
drugs more than 200 times each year and half are good candidates 
for professional treatment the bush administration says 
the national drug control strategy unveiled tuesday calls for a 
53 percent increase in federal funds for drug treatment from 604 
million in the current budget to 925 million in the next fiscal 
year 
the federal funds added to expected state and local 
contributions would increase the number of treatment slots from 
324000 to 650000 to 700000 said drug czar william bennett 
about 1 million people with serious drug problems could kick 
their habits on their own or with the help of friends family and 
clergy according to the strategy 
another million are so addicted so inclined this way no 
treatment and no kind of therapy is going to help them bennett 
said 
the strategy also calls for increasing the number of people 
getting treatment by urging states to consider expanding the use 
of civil commitment whereby addicts convicted of criminal offenses 
are sent by the courts to treatment facilities in lieu of or in 
addition to incarceration 
research indicates that voluntary and involuntary treatment 
patients do equally well 
only about 40 percent of those with the best chance of benefiting 
from drug treatment actually received such help in 1987 the 
strategy document said 
one of the problems with treatment is the lack of help available 
for cocaine addicts 
currently there are no proven successful treatment strategies 
comparable to those for heroin addiction the strategy said 
