<TEXT>
youngsters who look after themselves after school 
for 11 or more hours a week are twice as likely to abuse alcohol 
tobacco and marijuana as children who arent latchkey kids a 
report says 
the study of nearly 5000 eighthgraders in the los angeles and 
san diego areas found a higher risk of drug and alcohol abuse and 
smoking in twoparent as well as singleparent households and in 
affluent as well as poor ones 
the authors speculated that time spent alone promotes 
experimentation with drugs and alcohol 
the study is published in this months issue of pediatrics the 
journal of the american academy of pediatrics which is based in 
suburban elk grove village 
adolescents who abuse drugs and alcohol while caring for 
themselves may be manifesting a desire to display their sense of 
maturity and independence said the study 
the findings support recent articles that suggest some problem 
behavior among youngsters can be linked at least in part to the 
amount of time they spend without adult supervision particularly 
after school the authors said 
