the sun bremerton wash on the soviet economy 
in the latest of several developments that threaten perestroika 
the moscow city government has decided to bar nonresidents from 
buying items such as clothing from the soviet capitals stores due 
to scarcities 
that is far more serious than it might seem relatively speaking 
moscow has long been an oasis in the desert of soviet consumer 
goods every week hundreds of thousands of shoppers from elsewhere 
have flocked there in search of meat refrigerators and other 
merchandise they cannot find in their hometown stores 
in effect the soviets are moving toward internal protectionism 
this protectionism mirrors a new trend among other warsaw pact 
countries which are making it harder for each others tourists to 
take scarce goods home czechoslovakia and east germany for 
example recently outlawed foreign purchases of food and toilet 
paper the soviets responded with their own ban on exports of 
refrigerators and caviar 
whatever its immediate advantages for particular groups in the 
long run such protectionism will inevitably make the eastern blocs 
economic woes even worse thoughtful soviets realize this the 
government newspaper izvestia strongly denounced moscows new 
shopping rules 
gorbachevs entire reform agenda is in danger unless he can turn 
the economy around the only way to do that is to move far more 
boldly toward a free market not further away 
