<TEXT>
the american civil liberties union called the 
bush administrations antidrug strategy counterproductive and 
cynical wednesday saying it shortchanges prevention and 
treatment programs while putting overwhelming reliance on the 
criminal justice system 
ira glasser executive director of the 275000member 
organization told a news conference that the war on drugs outlined 
by president bush in his nationally televised speech tuesday night 
amounts to a fullfledged political hoax 
this is a joke glasser said it is a hoax on the public 
it cannot work 
in a statement released at the news conference the aclu said 
drug czar william bennetts longawaited proposal for the bush 
administrations war on drugs is not simply unworkable it is 
counterproductive and cynical 
it said the administrations plan will do little to lessen the 
problems caused by drug use while compromising civil liberties 
overcrowding prisons and costing the taxpayers millions of dollars 
the proposals overwhelming reliance on the criminal justice 
system its underfunding of treatment and prevention programs and 
its utter disregard for the everworsening conditions in our 
nations inner cities dooms it to certain failure the statement 
said 
also criticizing the administrations antidrug strategy were 
several other groups including the national association of criminal 
defense lawyers the criminal justice policy foundation and the 
national organization for the reform of marijuana laws known as 
norml 
in its statement the aclu asserted that bennetts proposal is 
little more than another attempt to fool the public into believing 
that prohibition can work when all the evidence shows that it 
cannot 
the new yorkbased civil liberties group assailed elements of the 
administrations plan including more drug testing of workers more 
penalties for firsttime and occasional users and more pretrial 
forfeiture of vehicles and other assets 
none of these measures will have a significant impact on the 
countrys drug problem all of them represent attacks on basic 
american values like the presumption of innocence the right to be 
free from unreasonable searches and seizures and the right to due 
process of the law it said 
neal r sonnett president of the national association of 
criminal defense lawyers said the administrations plan shows no 
leadership and dooms us to repeat the failures of the past 
instead of ensnaring more people into our already overburdened 
criminal justice system and bursting jails we need to find better 
ways to divert firsttime and nonviolent minor offenders into 
treatment rehabilitation and education programs sonnett said 
eric e sterling president of the criminal justice policy 
foundation another washingtonbased group spoke out in favoring of 
legalizing drugs 
congress can destroy the colombian cartel through legalization 
by changing the drug laws but there is one law congress can never 
repeal the law of supply and demand sterling said 
donald fiedler national director of norml contended that the 
administrations program amounts to declaring war on at least 25 
million fellow citizens who are leading productive lives but for 
their casual or regular use of marijuana 
