about 20 south korean movie directors 
stopped filming wednesday and began a hunger strike to protest the 
arrest of two colleagues who allegedly released snakes into theaters 
showing american films 
in a statement the directors demanded the release of the two 
arrested men and a halt to distribution of american films in south 
korea by the hollywoodbased universal international pictures 
the campaign against uip began in september three years after 
south korean authorities ended the monopolized distribution of 
american films by korean middlemen 
the korean movie industry received subsidies from the middlemen 
and film workers contend their monopoly should have been allowed to 
continue 
throwing snakes and liquid ammonia into theaters showing american 
films became a common form of protest 
on monday two directors were arrested for allegedly hiring a 
snake dealer to release nonpoisonous snakes into theaters showing 
uip films last year 
