<TEXT>
state agriculture officials 
announced today they will begin immediate spraying to protect 
californias 14 billion produce industry from an infestation of the 
voracious mediterranean fruit fly 
the decision required a declaration of an emergency by gov 
george deukmejian who signed the order today after 16 medflies were 
found in the mountain view area since last week said gera curry 
food and agriculture department spokeswoman 
the spraying of the pesticide malathion take place in northern 
californias santa clara county 
ground spraying was to begin about noon and an aerial spraying 
will be done on friday if the weather is clear the department said 
beginning sept 18 the state will also release 30 million 
sterile medflies a week until biologists decide the infestation is 
destroyed 
medflies lay eggs in 250 varieties of fruits and vegetables 
including all citrus fruits apples cherries avocados and tomatoes 
and are capable of devastating californias 14 billion annual 
agricultural industry 
when medfly eggs hatch the larvae feed on the fruit which spoil 
and fall to the ground 
immediate ground and aerial spraying of malathion was recommended 
tuesday by a group of international experts in pest eradication 
the advisory group which discussed the infestation during a 
conference call from such locations as guatemala hawaii and 
florida said other options available involve quarantine or 
treatment only of the affected plants 
under state law aerial spraying of malathion requires at least 
24hour notice to each home in the area a state study in 1987 found 
no damage to peoples health as a result of largescale spraying in 
the early 1980s 
about 300 members of the california conservation corps were 
distributing leaflets today to about 100000 homes in the area the 
leaflets described time and place of spraying possible health 
hazards and steps to protect vehicles 
a 198081 medfly infestation in santa clara county caused a 
bitter debate over the use of chemical sprays helicopter spraying 
of malathion over eight san franciscoregion counties eventually 
wiped out the pests 
an infestation in the los angeles area last year cost 2 million 
to eradicate by way of malathion spraying and the release of 700 
million sterile flies another infestation in 198082 cost 100 
million 
in the early 1980s the state spent more than 100 million to 
eradicate the pest in parts of central california and los angeles 
</TEXT>
