<TEXT>
a federal appeals court today lifted an 
injunction blocking the cutting of oldgrowth timber on federal land 
in oregon but kept alive a lawsuit by environmentalists to protect 
the northern spotted owl 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals in san francisco ruled that 
a federal law backed by the timber industry prohibited the 
conservationists from challenging the us bureau of land 
managements logging plans 
the court removed an injunction it had imposed june 7 the 
injunction had prohibited cutting of oldgrowth timber within 21 
miles of spotted owl nests 
scientists say the owl depends on old growth timber for its 
survival and the us fish and wildlife service is studying the owl 
for possible designation as a threatened species 
its a stunning defeat for the conservation community said 
boyd peters a spokesman for the environmental group headwaters 
it wasnt immediately clear when loggers would allowed to go in 
to cut down more old growth timber which is generally considered 
trees that are hundreds of years old such trees coveted by loggers 
for their superior timber 
timber interests argued the injunction posed a threat to the 
pacific northwests timber supply and would cost thousands of people 
their jobs in wood products plants and mills 
the appeals court said that under law environmentalists could 
not challenge an existing blm timber management plan 
however the court revived the conservationists claims that the 
destruction of spotted owl habitat violated the migratory bird 
treaty act and federal oregon and california law 
a lowercourt judge had dismissed those claims saying they 
should have raised earlier 
the appeals court ordered us district judge helen frye to 
reconsider the claims saying environmental groups had acted as soon 
as they could after getting new information about possible danger to 
the owl 
</TEXT>
