<TEXT>
seymour hersh who 20 years ago was the first 
reporter to describe the my lai massacre says he was put onto the 
story by a telephone tip from a lawyer he barely knew 
writing in the octobernovember issue of memories magazine hersh 
recalls working as a freelance writer in washington on oct 22 
1969 when he got a telephone call from geoffrey cowan 
cowan told hersh about a rumor hed heard the army was going to 
secretly courtmartial a soldier at fort benning ga for killing 
civilians in south vietnam he asked hersh if he was interested 
to this day im not sure why i was writes hersh who had 
covered the pentagon for the associated press and had come away 
hating the war convinced that its emphasis on body counts and 
statistical success was turning the officer corps into 
professional liars 
but hersh says he also came to realize that many officers at the 
pentagon were as troubled as i was maybe it was that 
understanding dimly perceived that set me to work on cowans tip 
hersh confirmed the massacre with a pentagon source and visited a 
military defense lawyer in utah he went to fort benning eventually 
tracked down the key subject of the investigation lt william l 
calley jr and broke the story of how a platoon of charlie company 
commanded by calley killed about 400 civilians in the hamlet of my 
lai 4 on march 16 1968 
when he located calley in quarters ordinarily reserved for senior 
officers hersh writes i think he understood in some primitive 
way that we would talk and then i would write and his life would 
never be the same again he was right neither would mine 
initially accused of killing 109 civilians calley was convicted 
in 1970 of murdering 22 but served only three years before his 
release hersh won a pulitzer prize for his reporting on the 
incident 
