<TEXT>
sen patrick leahy dvt chairman of the 
agriculture committee called wednesday for congress to redirect 
us foreign aid to protect the world environment 
he told the senate foreign relations committee he will introduce 
a bill aimed at helping countries develop economic alternatives that 
will save forests and other natural resources 
we must make some tough choices focusing limited foreign aid 
funds on critical problems tropical deforestation and energy waste 
and in critical nations even if we dont have programs there now 
he said 
according to a statement by leahys office the international 
climate change and tropical forestry act of 1989 would be aimed at 
providing more aid to third world countries where development often 
means the destruction of tropical rain forests 
the bill would authorize 10 million through the agency for 
international development for programs to improve energy efficiency 
and the use of renewable energy resources in developing nations it 
would also call for stronger forestry research programs promote 
international cooperation on reducing gas emissions 
leahy said rising world temperatures threaten farming in the 
united states and other countries of the northern hemisphere many 
scientists believe burning tropical forests and increased use of 
coal and oil as fuels contribute to a general warming of the globe 
leahy has already introduced a bill that would force lower 
emissions within the united states of gases such as carbon dioxide 
believed to have the same effect 
global climate change is a major threat to agriculture 
throughout the world he said 
with a doubling of carbon dioxide corn production could be 
reduced by 25 percent increased temperatures could cut world rice 
production by as much as 40 percent 
leahy told reporters india and brazil are countries where more 
us aid could be used india gets some direct us aid mostly in 
loans to buy us food but the program has been reduced in recent 
years brazil does not get us economic help 
most direct us aid goes to countries seen as important to us 
security such as israel egypt and the philippines 
but foreign military sales is not necessarily where we should 
target leahy said in the interview traditional aid wont help 
the environment 
</TEXT>
