an 80yearold man fighting deportation over 
accusations he committed nazi atrocities has a constitutional right 
to refuse to answer questions about his wartime activities in 
latvia a federal judge has ruled 
the fear of edgars inde are reasonable that he will be prosecuted 
for war crimes if his us citizenship is revoked and he is 
deported us district judge paul magnuson said tuesday 
the ruling means inde may invoke his fifth amendment right in the 
civil proceeding against him instituted in a lawsuit for deportation 
by the us justice department in 1988 
the minneapolis man is accused of belonging to a political police 
organization that helped nazi ss troops execute thousands of latvian 
jews in 1941 the government sued inde on grounds that he lied about 
his wartime activities when he applied for entry into the united 
states following the war 
inde has denied that he was involved in the execution of jews 
the united states does not prosecute war criminals but some 
countries including israel the soviet union and west germany have 
done so 
indes attorney ivars berzins of babylon ny told magnuson 
at a hearing in may that inde fears he will be deported to one of 
those three countries and prosecuted for war crimes 
this is a civil proceeding in name only berzins said our 
client stands accused of nothing less than murder he has a real 
fear of foreign prosecution 
magnuson said in his order that indes fear is not trifling or 
imaginary in view of the nature of the charges it is reasonable to 
assume that the only country willing to accept him in the event of 
deportation would be one that would prosecute him 
berzins reached at his office by telephone wednesday declined 
to comment on the ruling and refused to say what the next step in 
the proceedings would be 
telephone messages for comment from alan held attorney for the 
us justice department were not immediately returned 
the justice department had argued that inde may decline to answer 
questions only if he fears prosecution in the united states the 
department also contends it is unlikely any other country would 
prosecute inde for war crimes 
magnusons order overturns one issued in may by us magistrate 
floyd boline boline said that fear of foreign prosecution is not a 
basis for claiming privilege against selfincrimination and that any 
statements made by inde in a deposition could be sealed to protect 
him from foreign prosecution 
magnuson said sealing the transcript might not adequately protect 
inde 
