<TEXT>
financially strapped federal agencies lack the 
staff and equipment to handle a major oil spill in the great lakes 
and plans for such an emergency are weak experts told a senate 
panel wednesday 
the government also is doing a poor job of preventing and 
cleaning up the hundreds of smaller oil and toxic chemical leaks 
that pollute the great lakes each year witnesses told the 
governmental affairs subcommittee on oversight of government 
management 
the subcommittee launched an investigation of the federal 
governments handling of great lakes spills in the wake of the march 
24 exxon valdez disaster off the alaskan coast sen carl levin 
dmich the subcommittee chairman said the lakes situation was 
disquieting 
the great lakes are far more vulnerable to spills than most 
people realize and there are far more inadequacies in our spill 
response and prevention capabilities than we can or should 
tolerate said sen carl levin dmich chairman of the 
subcommittee 
the question is whether enough welltrained people and equipment 
can be transported to a major spill quickly enough to contain it 
said david f hales director of the michigan department of natural 
resources 
im afraid the answer is that we are not prepared hales 
said 
the largest tankers on the lakes hold only 120000 barrels less 
than 9 percent of what the exxon valdez carried hales acknowledged 
but levin and other witnesses said a spill from such a vessel could 
be just as damaging because the lakes are less capable of dispersing 
pollutants than the oceans 
the great lakes are a closed system a bathtub whose waters 
can take hundreds of years to leave the system levin said 
hales criticized the oil industry for announcing plans to open 
five emergency response centers for oil spills along the ocean 
coasts but none along the lakes 
the american petroleum institute said in a statement its new york 
response office would handle great lakes spills equipment from 
the center could be rapidly airlifted to any great lakes port 
the statement said 
an increase in spills in recent years has occurred simultaneously 
with environmental protection agency cutbacks on inspections of 
onshore oil storage facilities and the coast guards 50 percent cut 
in marine safety and environmental protection programs since 1980 
levin said 
there were 401 oil and chemical spills in the lakes in 1986 384 
in 1987 and 492 in 1988 some were large such as the 1984 discharge 
of 1 million gallons of fuel oil from a storage tank in new york and 
a 1984 spill of 200000 gallons of toxic ammonia from a michigan 
industrial plant 
