<TEXT>
american officials did not dispute japanese charges 
made during trade talks that us spending habits and the nations 
budget deficit are part of the cause of the bilateral trade 
imbalance 
the united states should save more cut its budget deficit and 
encourage longerterm thinking by its business leaders japanese 
officials told their american colleagues tuesday in talks on 
structural solutions to the japanese trade surplus 
american officials attending the talks said they would seriously 
consider japanese suggestions for improving us export 
competitiveness including a call for increased spending on 
workforce training and education and more emphasis on the longterm 
implications of business decisions 
japanese officials said the huge us budget deficit and low 
savings rate were major causes of the more than 50 billion 
bilateral trade imbalance 
economists say that when americans do not save enough to pay the 
us government budget deficit the government must borrow from 
foreigners including japanese who get the money to lend by selling 
goods to the us 
as long as americans prefer to buy japanese goods rather than put 
their money in the bank and japanese prefer to save their money 
rather than spend it the imbalance will continue the economists 
say 
american and japanese trade policymakers generally agree that 
barriers to specific products the focus of trade negotiations in 
the past now account for only a small part of the imbalance most 
of the imbalance is caused they say by macroeconomic factors such 
as savings rates and government spending patterns 
we agreed with a great deal with the suggestions of our 
japanese colleagues and hope they will take just as seriously our 
suggestions said richard mccormack undersecretary of state for 
economic affairs and the leader of the us delegation when our 
japanese colleagues said our savings rate is too low we were in 
total agreement with them 
in talks monday american officials told japan it should 
encourage people to spend rather than save streamline its 
complicated distribution system and loosen the tightknit business 
ties that often exclude newcomers 
the us officials stressed that talks on eliminating the 
structural causes of the trade imbalance dubbed the structural 
impediments initiative were expected to produce concrete results 
on both sides of the pacific 
mccormack said the united states had already established a 
working group to study the us savings rate he said some progress 
had been made in encouraging americans to save more raising the 
personal savings rate from 32 percent of the us gross national 
product in 1987 to 54 percent this year 
both japanese and us participants declined to comment on 
specific policy changes that might result from the talks which are 
slated to resume in washington nov 67 
we hope and expect some changes could be implemented before 
the interim report next spring mccormack said i myself am 
optimistic that these talks will result in tangible changes 
japanese officials who on monday were urged to increase public 
spending to improve the quality of life in japan and to end 
exclusionary business practices that limit entry into their markets 
were more reserved in their comments 
although we havent come up with any concrete answers to those 
questions raised by either side i think it was significant that 
each side has come to know the others point of view said 
michihiko kunihiro deputy foreign minister for economic affairs 
the response of japanese officials to the us recommendations 
was mixed 
construction minister shozo harada said the us call to increase 
the amount of japans land available for residential housing 
construction was realistic and urgent 
but finance minister ryutaro hashimoto told japanese reporters 
there is no need to obey the us calls 
hashimoto said the us tactical approach of emphasizing how the 
structural reforms they suggested would benefit japanese consumers 
put his government in the uncomfortable position of having to 
explain why such improvements cannot be done 
the us officials said the structural reforms they suggested 
would both reduce the trade imbalance with japan and give japanese 
consumers access to a wider variety of products at lower prices 
spending more on highways parks sewers and medical facilities 
in japan they said would improve the quality of life for ordinary 
japanese and redistribute the nations massive wealth 
the two nations turned to a structural approach to trade reforms 
after success in lifting trade barriers such as tariffs failed to 
eliminate japans huge surpluses with the united states and other 
industrialized nations 
