a former executive of wall streets goldman sachs 
amp co has pleaded guilty to a felony mail fraud charge for trading 
on inside information 
the plea on tuesday by robert m freeman the former head of risk 
arbitrage at the prestigious investment house was part of an 
agreement with federal prosecutors announced aug 17 risk arbitrage 
is the speculative investment in stocks of possible takeover targets 
in entering the plea freeman became one of the most prominent 
people to plead guilty in the aftermath of the ivan boesky insider 
trading scandal that rocked wall street nearly three years ago 
freeman admitted that he used inside information when he ordered 
the sale of beatrice companies inc stock in january 1986 
i knew it was wrong at the time sir freeman told us 
district judge pierre leval 
he could be sentenced to up to five years in prison 186 
million in fines and additional restitution leval scheduled 
sentencing for nov 16 
the 47yearold securities professional read a sevenpage 
statement that detailed the events on which his guilty plea was 
based 
he said he received confirmation of a rumor from martin siegel 
then a vice president at kidder peabody amp co about a problem with 
the planned leveraged buyout of beatrice by the investment firm of 
kohlberg kravis roberts amp co 
when martin siegel confirmed the rumor i did not believe that 
he was authorized by kkr to do so and i knew i was not entitled to 
trade on that information freeman said 
after the conversation on jan 8 1986 he said he ordered the 
sale of certain beatrice securities in a company account in a 
customers account and in his own personal account 
