<TEXT>
twentyone european airlines wednesday 
proposed a europewide air traffic control system to replace the 
national systems currently in place 
the airlines called on european governments to convene a 
ministerial conference to set a timetable for creating the single 
atc system 
the brusselsbased association of european airlines said that 
europes present fragmented approach based on 22 national atc 
systems with 42 control centers is costly and inefficient 
these centers operate with different levels of performance and 
technology with no commonly agreed standards and a lack of 
compatibility between the different systems said aea secretary 
general karl heinz neumeister 
according to aea the current system has led to a crisis in 
european air travel as delays of more than 15 minutes reached 30 
percent of european flights in june and july those delays cost 
airlines passengers and the european economy about 42 billion a 
year aea said 
moreover a europewide atc system could mean direct savings of 
500 million a year at present air traffic levels and 800 million 
a year when future growth is taken into account the group estimated 
air traffic control services in the 22 countries belonging to the 
european civil aviation conference cost 16 billion the same as 
the us air traffic control system according to the aea the us 
system however handles more than three times as many flights 
the aea study estimates that air traffic in europe could have 
been handled by six enroute facilities instead of the present 42 
the savings would far exceed the 22 billion national authorities 
are planning to spend on air traffic control over the next few 
years aea said 
it proposed a twotiered structure for a future european atc 
system at an operational level the group proposed the creation of 
a central holding company jointly owned by governments and private 
interests its main functions would be to finance air traffic 
control in europe direct investments and reduce the number of atc 
facilities over the longterm 
a central holding company for air traffic control would assure 
that investments were made for the system as a whole in contrast to 
the current poorly coordinated spending by spearate national 
authorities the aea said 
governments could coordinate their policies in safety security 
and political matters through the european organization for the 
safety of air navigation eurocontrol under the aea proposal 
eurocontrol is a brusselsbased intergovernmental body with 11 
members 
though efforts have been made to coordinate european air traffic 
control they have been insufficient so far aea said 
eurocontrol called the aea proposals an interesting 
contribution to the debate on the future of air traffic control in 
europe eurocontrol also defended its own record saying it has 
already taken over the task of developing a central flow 
management unit for western europe which will be based in 
brussels 
</TEXT>
