<TEXT>
a former savings and loan executive has been found 
guilty of using more than 55000 in thrift funds to contribute to 
political campaigns and hire women from topless bars to accompany 
sampl officials on trips 
former vernon savings and loan president patrick g king a 
former state trooper and once the states secondranking thrift 
regulator was convicted tuesday of charges including conspiracy and 
fraud 
king could receive 65 years in prison and fines up to 500000 at 
sentencing nov 2 
mr king was an important kingpin in the savings and loan 
industry attorney general dick thornburgh said in a statement 
his conviction sends a message that no matter how high up the 
corporate ladder the wrongdoing was committed it will not go 
unprosecuted 
the government had charged king approved inflated expense 
vouchers and bogus bonus payments to reimburse employees for 
political contributions in 1986 and thus circumvent campaign 
contribution laws 
some of the contributions went to house speaker jim wright 
dtexas rep jack kemp rny and sen alan cranston dcalif 
but prosecutors said the politicians were not aware where the 
contributions came from 
in addition king was accused of paying women recruited at 
topless bars to accompany vernon officials and l linton bowman iii 
head of the regulating texas savings and loan department on two 
outofstate trips 
testimony indicated king approved payments of 100 to 200 per 
woman 
vernon was shut down in 1987 by federal regulators in a 13 
billion bailout 
king was the first vernon official to go to trial although 
others have pleaded guilty or been granted immunity for cooperation 
in the investigation of vernon often cited as one of the worst 
examples of abuses in the industry 
